  "summary": "Muji and the narrator arrive at Professor Nakamura's room on the fourth floor. Muji requests confidentiality and enters the room, leaving the narrator to wait in the hallway for thirty minutes while reading Ellery Queen's \"The Dutch Shoe Mystery.\" When Muji emerges, he indicates the meeting went well but remains secretive. They return to Kyoto City after nine o'clock, where the narrator observes the eerie, greenish-white glow of the city lights.\n\nThe narrator visits Ophelia, who is in a weakened state and speaks cryptically about everything crumbling the next day. Afterward, the narrator encounters Mr. Sugiyama (referred to as Kanai), who appears unsteady, possibly from drinking. Kanai entrusts the narrator with a \"mist drawing\" and expresses a desire to protect someone. He notes that Mukae believes the case will be solved the following day.\n\nIn a subsequent conversation, a talkative Kaname reveals a pattern regarding the Mirai family: women who enter the family tend to die early. He suggests that the family structure lacks women and that this is not merely coincidence. Kaname mentions that his grandmother, Lady Hinata, lived a long life, which broke the superstition, but he suspects that Setsuko was brought into the family as a foster daughter to serve as a substitute to appease this perceived fate.",
